revision.text:
'''Accentology''' involves a systematic analysis of word or phrase [[Stress (linguistics)|stress]]. Sub-areas of accentology include [[Germanic languages|Germanic]] accentology,<ref> {{cite book | last1 = Liberman | first1 = Anatoly | title = Germanic Accentology | publisher = U of Minnesota Press | year = 1982 | pages = 410 | isbn = 9780816658183}}</ref> [[Balto-Slavic languages|Balto-Slavic]] accentology,<ref name="isbn90-420-3332-0">{{cite book |author=Rick Derksen; Tijmen Pronk |title=Accent Matters: Papers on Balto-Slavic accentology. (Studies in Slavic and General Linguistics) |publisher=Rodopi |location=Amsterdam |year=2011 |pages= |isbn=90-420-3332-0 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=}}</ref> [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] accentology,<ref name="isbn0-19-927960-8">{{cite book |author=Philomen Probert |title=Ancient Greek accentuation: synchronic patterns, frequency effects, and prehistory |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford [Oxfordshire] |year=2006 |pages= |isbn=0-19-927960-8 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=}}</ref> and [[Japanese language|Japanese]] accentology.<ref name="isbn4-87297-794-7">{{cite book |author=Shigeki Kaji |title=Proceedings of the symposium Cross-Linguistic Studies of Tonal Phenomena, Tonogenesis, Japanese Accentology, and Other Topics: December 12-14, 2000, Gakushi Kaikan, Tokyo |publisher=Institute for the Study of Languages and Cultures of Asia and Africa, Tokyo University of Foreign Studies |location=Tokyo |year=2001 |pages= |isbn=4-87297-794-7 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=}}</ref>

