{{Orphan|date=August 2011}}
{{Infobox artifact | name = The Starving of Saqqara | image = | image2 = | image_caption = | material =Limestone | size ={{Convert|67|cm|in|abbr=on}}, {{Convert|80|kg|lb|abbr=on}} | writing =Unknown script | created =Unknown period | discovered =Egypt, early 20th century | location =[[Concordia University]] | id = }}
'''The Starving of Saqqara''' is the name given to a statue of suspected [[Prehistoric Egypt|Pre-dynastic Egyptian]] origins. The statue, of two nude beings (possible a male and female) with large skulls and thin bodies, seated, also has writing on the back of one of the figures<ref>{{cite web|title=The Starving of Saqqara sculpture|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/concordiauniversity/5934422523/|publisher=flickr|accessdate=4 October 2012|author=Concordia University|date=March 14, 2007}}</ref> that has yet to be identified. Traces of dark pigment suggest that it was once painted.
Vincent and Olga Diniacopoulos, who amassed a large collection of antiquities, brought the work to Canada in the 1950s. The sculpture was exhibited in the 1950s at their family-owned Galerie Ars Classica on [[Sherbrooke Street]] in [[Montreal]]. The name [[Saqqara]] refers to the burial ground of [[Memphis, Egypt]]. How the name came to be attached to the artifact is not known.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cmll.concordia.ca/diniacopoulos/csi/|title=CSI Montreal: Concordia Sculpture Investigation|last=Concordia University|work=Diniacopoulos Antiquities Collection|accessdate=18 March 2011}}</ref>
The statue has been at Concordia University since 1999. Experts from the [[University of Cambridge]], the [[British Museum]], the [[Brooklyn Museum]], the [[Israel Museum]] and the [[Royal Ontario Museum]] have all been consulted, without success.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/offbeat/story/2011/03/17/starving-of-saqqara-statue-concordia-mystery.html|title=Sculpture mystery baffles Concordia researchers|date=Mar 17, 2011|work=[[CBC.ca]]|accessdate=18 March 2011}}</ref>
The script has been determined to not be [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]], [[Demotic (Egyptian)|Demotic]], [[Egyptian language|Egyptian]], [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], or [[Syriac language|Syriac]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://montrealgazette.com/opinion/Experts+crack+Concordia+sculpture+riddle/4453206/story.html|title=Experts can't crack Concordia sculpture riddle|last=Curran|first=Peggy|date=March 17, 2011|work=[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]]|accessdate=18 March 2011}}</ref>
One expert, Clarence Epstein, suggests that it represents a pair of conquered captives.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sott.net/articles/show/225917-Canadian-university-puts-ancient-mysterious-sculpture-on-display|title=Canadian university puts ancient, mysterious sculpture on display|last=Boswell|first=Randy|date=16 Mar 2011|work=The Vancouver Sun|publisher=Sott.net|accessdate=18 March 2011}}</ref>
The sculpture was displayed to the public from March 16 to 18, 2011. It was viewable at the atrium of Concordia’s Engineering, Computer Science and Visual Arts Integrated Complex.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pasthorizons.com/index.php/archives/03/2011/the-mystery-of-the-starving-of-saqqara|title=The mystery of 'The Starving of Saqqara'|date=March 16, 2011|work=Past Horizons|accessdate=25 March 2011}}</ref>
